metadata.name: VOYAGERS #226
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from looping gestures in a virtual void.

Voyagers is an exploration of automated gestures and screenspace layering effects. Each brush stroke sweeps through the canvas leaving a trail of color that either disappears or mixes with adjacent colors. The image slowly builds up to achieve an equilibrium between the rhythm of the gestures and the interaction of color values. These colors are quantized and dithered to produce chunky, textured, blocks of light that reify the materiality of the screen and the pixel. Two aspect ratios are possible, each with its own material relationship to screen-based work, 1:1 and 4:3 (vertical).

Press 's' to save looping animated GIF (live mode only).
Press 'p' to pause the animation.
Press 'c' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Other ways #2
metadata.description:
Inspired by Paul Klee’s painting « Highways and byways », « Other ways » propose to build your own and unique generative painting.

7 features, including 4 main styles, 8 color palettes, 5 different parameters of the generative process.


Please note that the preview image is more saturated than the real token due to fxhash GPU management.

In Open Live window, press « s » to save the current image.
To get a High Resolution Image : press « r » to change the resolution for high definition, the image will reload and you can then use « s » to save the image (you can change DP in the URL to  a greater value for an even larger resolution in case you want to print it big).
This project is dimensionless, the Preview and OpenLive images are the same.

This artwork was created using p5js and scribble.

metadata.name: Eyeshadow Roses #94
metadata.description:
"Eyeshadow Roses" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Painterly roses randomly overprinted with heavy streaks of ink. 

The roses grow by a sequence of three spirals, every new spiral smaller and superimposed on the former.  After the roses are fully formed, a random mask of heavy ink is algorithmically screened over the flowers in a pattern of horizontal or vertical lines, occasionally fully flooding the painting. The accumulation of choices evokes graffiti or printmaking. The sequence of choices are interpreted by the computer according to the algorithm. The beauty of these choices are determined by the viewer.

Each piece takes roughly 10 seconds to generate.

Artist: @sarah_ridgley
Press [s] to save the image
JavaScript / p5js | script size: 11kb

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #250
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

NFT License

metadata.name: Wandering Nets #10
metadata.description:
Wandering Nets is a digital kinetic light sculpture by Matt Ebb.

Networks of light are created and connected via random walks in space and colour. Emergent structures are revealed by the ambient interaction, tension and collision of these networks within themselves and orbiting shadowed spherical bodies.

The piece is the result of several months of custom development in realtime volume rendering. The scene data is generated in javascript and rendered with a bespoke GLSL raytracer - no external libraries are used.

This is a graphically intensive shader. By default it will adaptively adjust sampling quality to target 30fps, though a reasonably fast GPU is recommended for best results. 

Mouse drag: Orbit the camera in 3D to explore compositions
[ and ] keys: Override the adaptive samples per pixel lower or higher to trade noise for framerate

March 2022

metadata.name: Sand Flow #4
metadata.description:
bstract generative art that simulates sandpainting.

"Sandpainting is the art of pouring coloured sands, and powdered pigments from minerals or crystals,
or pigments from other natural or synthetic sources onto a surface to make a fixed or unfixed sand painting.
Sand paintings have a long established cultural history in numerous social groupings around the globe."

Created from 100% code and math.

(Generation time is a little longer on this work (10-15 sec.), please be patient)

Hi-res. options:

- press 'i' to save .png with resolution = 1000px x 1000px
- press 't' to save .png with resolution = 2000px x 2000px
- press 's' to save .png with resolution = 6000px x 6000px

Created using p5js.

@Mutart, May, 2022.

metadata.name: Remake // Remodel #12
metadata.description:
Remake // Remodel is inspired by early computer art pioneers and a love of minimal and monochromatic art.

This artwork is an expansion upon, and takes inspiration from, Reiner Schneeberger’s “Untitled 5”, which was featured in “Computer Graphics and Art” Vol 3 No. 2, published in May 1978.
